Creating a new feature called months since hosting for feature engineering to use within the recipe. Mutating host_response_time, property_type, and room_type to factors. host_response_time could also be factorized within the recipe (see question 4 comments).

airbnb_clean <- airbnb_clean %>%
  mutate(months_since_hosting = as.integer(interval(start = host_since, end = today()) / months(1)))

airbnb_clean$host_response_time<-factor(airbnb_clean$host_response_time, levels = c("a few days or more","within a day","within a few hours","within an hour"))
airbnb_clean$property_type<-factor(airbnb_clean$property_type)
airbnb_clean$room_type<-factor(airbnb_clean$room_type)

Splitting the airbnb_clean dataset to create train and test datasets.

Setting the seed to 123 for reproducibility.

set.seed(123)

airbnb_split<-initial_split(airbnb_clean)

airbnb_train<-training(airbnb_split)
airbnb_test<-testing(airbnb_split)

Question 2

Applying a 10 fold cross validation in the training process.

Setting the seed to 123 for reproducibility.

set.seed(123)

airbnb_folds<-vfold_cv(data = airbnb_train, v = 10)

Question 3

Steps for question 3:

  • Creating a recipe to apply on airbnb_train with multiple feature engineering steps.

  • Creating a metrics set to evaluate the modelâs performance during predictions

  • Creating a workflow to include an algorithm boosted trees model and the previously created recipe

airbnb_recipe<-recipe(formula = log_price ~ ., data = airbnb_train) %>%
  
  step_rm(host_id,host_since,first_review,last_review,n_na_cols,price) %>% 
  
#median was used as imputing strategy for numerical features to avoid the possible presence of outliers influencing the outcome
  
  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors())%>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  
# step_novel(all_nominal()) should be included if room_type and property_type are not factorised before the splitting of the dataset into training and testing.
# step_noval allows the program to deal with previously unseen factor levels.
  
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())%>%
  
# step_string2factor(host_response_time, levels = c("a few days or more","within a day","within a few hours","within an hour"), ordered=TRUE) could be implemented instead of the steps implemented in question 1. This step can only be used for host_response_time and not for room and property type because of the absence of ordered levels for the last features.
  
  step_mutate(across(where(is.logical), ~ as.numeric(.))) %>%
  step_naomit()%>%
  
# step_zv was included to avoid issues regarding zero variance features. skip=TRUE was necessary to ensure the consistency in data set structure and avoid issues regarding data frames shapes mismatch later in question 7
  
  step_zv(all_predictors(), skip=TRUE)

airbnb_metrics<-metric_set(rmse,mae,rsq,mape)

xgboost_spec <- boost_tree(
  mtry = tune(),
  trees = tune(),
  min_n = tune(),
  tree_depth = tune(),
  learn_rate = tune()
) %>%
  set_mode('regression') %>%
  set_engine('xgboost')

airbnb_wf<- workflow()%>%
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)%>%
  add_model(xgboost_spec)

Question 4

Tuning a grid to incorporate within the steps and select the best model according to RMSE.

Once the best model is identified, the workflow is finilized and fit over airbnb_split.

get_coefs <- function(x) {
  extract_fit_parsnip(x) %>% tidy()
}

set.seed(123)

#grid_random was chosen instead of grid_control for running time purposes. Setting grid_control with the size of hyperparameters to tune present would result in a enormous number of models to be fitted within each fold, making the run time unbearable. For this reason a grid_random with size=10 was chosen such that the ten models to fit witin each fold are created randomly matching hyperparameters.

airbnb_grid <- grid_random(
  trees(range = c(100, 1000)),
  learn_rate(range = c(0.01, 0.1)),
  tree_depth(range = c(3, 8)),
  min_n(range = c(5, 30)),
  finalize(mtry(), airbnb_train),
  size = 10  
)


rs <- tune_grid(
  airbnb_wf,
  resamples = airbnb_folds,  
  metrics = airbnb_metrics,
  control = control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE, verbose = TRUE),
  grid = airbnb_grid,
  set.seed(123)
)

plot_neighbourhood_map <- function(neighbourhood_name) {
  
  # Filter using the correct column name for neighbourhoods
  neighbourhood_data <- airbnb_clean %>%
    filter(neighbourhood_group_cleansed == neighbourhood_name)
  
  # Creating a color palette based on the feature diff in the data set representing the prediction error
  pal <- colorNumeric(
    palette = c("blue", "orange"),
    domain  = neighbourhood_data$diff
  )
  
  leaflet(neighbourhood_data) %>%
    addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
    addCircleMarkers(
      lng = ~longitude, lat = ~latitude,
      radius = 4,
      color = ~pal(diff),
      stroke = FALSE, fillOpacity = 0.9,
      popup = ~paste(
        "Actual Price:", round(log_price, 2), "<br>",
        "Predicted Price:", round(pred, 2), "<br>",
        "Error:", round(diff, 2)
      )
    ) %>%
    addLegend(
      "bottomright",
      pal = pal,
      values = ~diff,
      title = paste("Prediction Error in", neighbourhood_name),
      opacity = 0.8
    )
}

# Create a vector of unique neighbourhood names from the correct column
neighbourhoods <- unique(airbnb_clean$neighbourhood_group_cleansed)

# Plot the map for each neighbourhood
for (n in neighbourhoods) {
  print(plot_neighbourhood_map(n))
}

Question 8

Predicting neighborhood prices on an apartment for 4 people with 2 bedrooms, 2 beds, 1 bathroom and a cleaning fee of 20 EUR. We then calculated the average yearly return for each neighborhood and the number of years it would take to recover the investment (price house/yearly returns).

Based on the 3 million EUR budget set, we chose the best combination of investments within the budget that minimize the recovery time. A greedy algorithm will select the investments to maximize returns while minimizing recovery time and remaining below the budget.

source('create_sample.R')

#Creating an empty dataframe to collect all necessary informations for the analysis of the investment
results <- data.frame(
  neighbourhood = character(nrow(avg_prices)),
  returns = numeric(nrow(avg_prices)),
  average_price = numeric(nrow(avg_prices)),
  recovery_time = numeric(nrow(avg_prices))
)

for (i in 1:nrow(avg_prices)) {
  #Extracting the neighborhood and occupancy rate
  n <- avg_prices$neighbourhood[i]
  occupation <- avg_prices$pct_year_occupation[i]
  
  new_sample <- create_sample(
    df = airbnb_clean, 
    df_prices = avg_prices,
    origin_sample = sample(1:nrow(airbnb_clean), size = 1, replace = FALSE), 
    neighbourhood_new = n, 
    cleaning_fee_new = 20
  )
  
  predicted_log_price <- predict(airbnb_predictor, new_data = new_sample)
  #Since predictions give the log_price, we must take the exponent of it to extract the actual predicted price
  predicted_price <- exp(predicted_log_price$.pred)
  recovery <- avg_prices$avg_price[i] / (predicted_price * (365 * occupation))
  
  #imputing data into the data frame
  results$neighbourhood[i] <- n
  results$returns[i] <- predicted_price * (365 * occupation)
  results$average_price[i] <- avg_prices$avg_price[i]
  results$recovery_time[i] <- recovery
}

#Visualizing whihc properties would take the least number of years to recover the initial investment
print(results[order(results$recovery_time), ])
         neighbourhood  returns average_price recovery_time
4       sants-montjuic 31689.87        299140      9.439610

2         ciutat vella 30400.17        392645     12.915882

3           sant marti 21272.39        435215     20.459146
10           les corts 34296.19        779088     22.716459
5  sarria-sant gervasi 29211.96        980439     33.562936
8               gracia 13220.23        500411     37.851919
#Implementing a greedy algorithm to define the investments to undertake
#The greedy_score allows us to obey the contraints of minimizing recovery time of the investment while maximizing the total returns from the property.
results$greedy_score <- results$returns / results$recovery_time

#We are ordering the results in descending order based on the new implemented variable
ordered_results <- results[order(-results$greedy_score), ]


#Setting up the constraints
budget <- 3000000
total_spent <- 0
selected_listings <- data.frame()

#The logic follows: if the first neighborhood ordered based on the greedy_score is within budget then we invest otherwise we check the next and so on.
for (i in 1:nrow(ordered_results)) {
  cost <- ordered_results$average_price[i]
  
  if ((total_spent + cost) <= budget) {
    total_spent <- total_spent + cost
    selected_listings <- rbind(selected_listings, ordered_results[i, ])
  } else {
    break
  }
}
#The investor should invest in the following neighborhoods assuming he buys one property per neighborhood at average price.
print(selected_listings)
